## PHASE 1: UNIVERSE CONSTRUCTION

### Step 1 — Build the Candidate Universe

The scanner constructs a complete list of public companies in the theme before evaluating any of them. This prevents cherry-picking well-known names.

**Search methodology:**
```
Search A: "[theme name] public companies stocks 2026"
Search B: "[theme name] ETF holdings components"
Search C: "[theme keyword] Russell 2000 small cap stocks"
Search D: "[theme keyword] IPO 2024 2025 2026"
Search E: "[adjacent theme] companies expanding into [theme]"
```

**Universe construction rules:**
- Include ALL companies found, not just familiar ones
- Flag companies that only appear in one of five searches as "low visibility" — these are potentially the most interesting
- Flag companies that appear in all five searches as "high visibility" — these are potentially already discovered
- Maximum universe size: 25 companies. If more than 25 appear, apply the first filter immediately (market cap ceiling)

**The Low Visibility Signal:**
If a company appears in Search C (Russell 2000) or Search D (recent IPO) but NOT in Search A (standard "stocks in theme"), it is a priority candidate. The market has not yet connected this company to the theme narrative. That is the information gap that creates 10x returns.

### Step 2 — Apply the Brutal First Filter

Immediately eliminate any company that fails any of these:
```
INSTANT ELIMINATIONS:
❌ Market cap above ceiling (default $5B, unless Mega-Winner
   Exception explicitly applied)
❌ Revenue below $50M (pre-revenue speculation, not investment)
❌ Gross margin below 50% (not a software/platform business)
❌ More than 3 of 9 forensic kill-shot flags active
❌ Real FCF negative with no credible path to positive
   within 24 months
❌ Company is a division of a conglomerate with no
   pure-play exposure
```

After the first filter: the universe should be 5–12 companies. More than 12 means the filter is too loose — tighten market cap ceiling. Fewer than 3 means the theme is too narrow — broaden to adjacent sub-themes.

