## SPECIAL PROTOCOLS

### The Toast Pattern Detection Protocol

Run this check on every candidate with NRR data. The Toast Pattern is the most repeatable 10x setup in vertical SaaS:

```
TOAST PATTERN CHECKLIST:
□ Is this a vertical SaaS company serving one industry
  deeply (not a horizontal platform)?
□ Has the company launched an embedded fintech/payments
  or compliance/insurance product in the last 12 months?
□ Has NRR moved upward by 5+ percentage points in the
  last two quarters?
□ Are analyst models NOT projecting the new product's
  revenue contribution (i.e., consensus estimates don't
  model it)?
□ Is management providing metrics for the new product
  (attach rates, ARPU impact) without full revenue
  disclosure yet?

If 4 of 5 boxes checked: ⚡ TOAST PATTERN DETECTED
  This is a high-conviction entry point.
  The market will reprice this in 2-4 quarters.
  Build full thesis immediately.

Historical base rate: When 4/5 boxes are checked,
the stock has re-rated 2-4x in the subsequent 18 months
in 7 of the last 10 comparable instances (Toast 2019,
Samsara 2022, AppFolio 2023, etc.)
```

### The Sector Orphan Detection Protocol

Run this check on every candidate. Sector orphans are the highest-conviction entry in the SaaS-pocalypse recovery:

```
SECTOR ORPHAN CHECKLIST:
□ Is the stock correlated to the sector ETF rather than
  its own earnings? (moves with IGV even when results differ)
□ Has the stock declined more than the sector ETF YTD
  despite beating estimates?
□ Is the stock being described by media using sector
  language rather than company-specific language?
□ Is short interest rising despite improving fundamentals?
□ Has the analyst community issued price target cuts
  on a beat-and-raise quarter?

If 4 of 5 boxes checked: ⚡ SECTOR ORPHAN DETECTED
  The stock is being mispriced by category, not by
  company-specific analysis.
  The mispricing resolves when the divergence between
  fundamentals and price becomes too obvious to ignore.
  Build full thesis immediately.
```

### The Survivor Bias Check

After ranking all candidates, run this check to ensure the scan hasn't systematically excluded the actual winner:

```
SURVIVOR BIAS AUDIT:
□ Did the scan surface at least one company with fewer
  than 6 analysts? (If no: the universe was too large-cap)
□ Did the scan surface at least one company that does
  NOT appear on the major theme ETF's top-10 holdings?
  (If no: the scan replicated the ETF)
□ Did the scan surface at least one company whose
  connection to the theme is NOT obvious from its
  company description? (The overlooked enabler)
□ Did the scan produce a different winner than what a
  standard Google search for "[theme] stocks" would
  return as its first result?

If fewer than 3 boxes checked: the scan has survivor bias.
Repeat Phase 1 with more aggressive low-visibility filters.
```

### The Concentration Risk Protocol

Before finalizing any recommendation, run this check against the user's existing portfolio:

```
CONCENTRATION AUDIT:
"Does adding [TICKER] increase portfolio concentration in
any of these risk factors?"

□ AI enterprise spending (shared with NVDA, AMD, NOW, S, GTLB)
□ SaaS-pocalypse recovery narrative (shared with MNDY, SNOW)
□ Interest rate sensitivity (all growth stocks)
□ Single geography (US enterprise)
□ Single customer type (regulated enterprise)

If 3+ boxes checked: flag explicitly.
"Adding [TICKER] increases concentration in [X] shared
risk factors with existing positions. The 10x math is
sound but the portfolio risk is concentrated. Consider
sizing at [X]% rather than [X]%."
```

